PARAGRAPH.#text: By Razak Musah Baba and Ian Walker LONDON--AbbVie Inc., ABBV Monday raised the midpoint of its full-year 2014 earnings-per-share guidance to reflect the strong underlying business performance year-to-date, the company said Monday. North Chicago, Ill.-based AbbVie, which was spun off from Abbott Laboratories in early 2013, said it has raised the midpoint of its full-year 2014 earnings-per-share guidance by six cents and now expects a full-year diluted earnings-per-share range of $3.06 to $3.16 on an adjusted basis, or $2.69 to $2.79 on a GAAP basis.

ABBV that it had made a 27.2 billion pound ($46.15 billion) takeover bid for the specialist in drugs to treat attention-deficit disorder and rare diseases, which it rejected. In the medium term Shire said it is targeting annual product sales of $6.5 billion by 2016.

Headlines.Author: Hester Plumridge
Headlines.Headline: Proposed Law Would Require More Drug-Trial Transparency

PARAGRAPH.#text: Drug companies and researchers will no longer be able to withhold the results of unfavorable clinical trials, if changes to European law are passed as expected next month. The new law would require the results of all trials plus a full clinical-study report to be published within a year of the trial ending. The European Parliament is to vote on the new legislation April 3, and it would come into force in 2016. Around half of all trial results go unpublished, according to current estimates, including a 2009 paper that looked at 677 studies conducted in different countries.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Proposed Law Would Require More Drug-Trial Transparency

Headlines.Author: Brent Kendall
Headlines.Headline: Supreme Court Rules Drug-Company Settlements Can Face Antitrust Scrutiny

PARAGRAPH.#text: The U.S. Supreme Court on Monday ruled that courts should give more scrutiny to pharmaceutical industry patent settlements that can delay the entry of generic drugs. The court's decision, in a case brought by the Federal Trade Commission, provided at least a partial victory for government antitrust enforcers because it reversed a lower-court ruling that was favorable to the drug industry. The ruling, however, didn't embrace the government's broadest argument against the industry settlements. The FTC for years has sought to prohibit settlements in which brand-name drug companies pay generic-drug makers to drop patent lawsuits that could lead to the earliest possible sales of their cheaper versions.

Headlines.Author: Joseph Walker
Headlines.Headline: Amgen Details Plan to Fight Patent Cliff, Lifts 2013 View

PARAGRAPH.#text: --Amgen to fight patent cliff with biosimilar, international expansion --Sees launching six biosimilars, beginning in 2017 --Raises 2013 per-share earnings outlook (Adds details in ninth paragraph and analyst comments in 13th paragraph.) Amgen Inc. AMGN said it will aggressively seek revenue over the next few years from international markets and by launching copycat drugs as the company prepares for a new phase in its history when many of its hallmark drugs lose patent protection. "Through the period of our patent expirations, we'll be able to grow earnings and cash flow," Chief Executive Robert Bradway said at a business review meeting with investors in New York.

Headlines.SeoHeadline: Ailing AstraZeneca Should Go Shopping for Deals
Headlines.Author: Jessica Hodgson
Headlines.Headline: Ailing AstraZeneca Should Go Shopping for Deals

PARAGRAPH.#text: Pascal Soriot, the new chief executive of AstraZeneca, said Thursday that the company didn't need to do a large acquisition to stem the hemorrhages in revenue it's suffering as drugs come off patent. The company has almost all the intellectual property and skills it needs in house to turbo-charge sales again, he said, with the help of some smart portfolio management and a few bolt-on deals.
